WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:01.360
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:01.580 --> 00:00:05.640
I don't think I'll be needing my full time after the excellent review done by Dr. Martin

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:07.080
about the journey of Belentamab.

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:13.120
So I'll try to script through some of my slides here, here are my disclosures, and just the

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:14.020
outline of my talk.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:18.840
I think I was going to cover some of the mechanisms and rebirth of Belentamab in multiple myeloma,

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:23.940
and also just do an across-trial comparison of where Belentamab stands compared to the

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:28.680
dominating world of bispecifics and CAR-T-cell therapy in myeloma, and then look at some

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.980
of the real world data, not just in myeloma, but also AL amyloidosis.

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:37.580
So just to highlight all the progress that's happening in the world of multiple myeloma,

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:42.120
I think every year or so we have a new therapy that's approved for treatment of patients

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:46.280
with multiple myeloma, and I think we are increasingly finding us in a place where we

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:49.800
have to find who are the right patients for this particular type of therapy.

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:55.620
And then I think this is a slide that I'll try to skip here because Dr. Martin covered

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:56.280
earlier on.

00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:58.540
But I think this covers the journey of all.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:04.740
The dream trials and they can assert the failures and successes of Belentamab and bringing it

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:07.700
to the FDA approval in 2025.

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:12.420
So thinking about the real world experience with Belentamab, these are some of the larger

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:15.400
studies that have been published in the past few years.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:20.120
So these studies have included anywhere from like 30 to like close to 200 patients.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:25.560
And the message is very clear that when Belentamab is used as a monotherapy, the real world outcomes

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:28.600
do match what we're seeing on the dream one and dream two trials.

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:52.380
We do see a little bit of under reporting of the popular toxicities in the real world

00:01:52.380 --> 00:01:56.660
data compared to what we have seen in the clinical trial, but overall this data is very

00:01:56.660 --> 00:01:58.560
similar to what was what we see in the clinical trial.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:00.920
We saw with the dream one and dream two trial.

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:05.860
I think at this point of time, what we are missing is the real world evidence of Belentamab

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:09.740
combinations and we did have an EAP open for the last couple of years.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:13.360
So maybe in the near future, we'll have some data that could actually come out from the

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:18.100
EAP and show that like, you know, the Belentamab combinations were equally successful compared

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:20.980
to how the trials were run.

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:26.220
Just another slide that I felt that, you know, was very important to bring out here as well,

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:28.520
which is like, you know, when dream seven and dream eight.

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:30.720
Results came out in 2024.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:33.840
I think it was amazing that Belentamab held its place.

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:40.880
It showed that using Belentamab combinations increased deep responses like CRs in patients.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:46.160
We saw MRD negativity in relapse, multiple myeloma patients, and we saw PFS and overall

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:47.160
survival benefit.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:52.040
So I think in that year itself, like these were amazing results that showed like, yeah,

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:55.640
this is making a huge comeback and we are going to be increasingly finding us in a place

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:58.480
where we have to find like, you know, the right patient.

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:02.000
And the right approach to using all these drugs available.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.280
But also like, you know, just recently we had the MAJESTIC-3 trial that was published

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:10.880
and we see when we look at the response rates, when we look at progression-free survival

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:15.980
curves out of the MAJESTIC-3 and CARTITUDE-4 trials, we can certainly point out which one

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:23.180
of the therapies are a true winner compared to the antibody drug conjugate.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:28.000
And then I put this slide on because I was going to pivot over to AL amyloidosis, and

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:28.440
it is a competition.

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:32.560
It is a complicated space where like when it comes to treating patients who have relapsed

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:37.680
or have not responded to the initial therapy, it is a messy world to get any type of therapies

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:38.980
approved for patients.

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:43.020
And we generally scramble between all the different choices that have some trial data

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:48.260
published of like, you know, treatment in AL amyloidosis, but we always emphasize on

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:50.760
enrolling patients to clinical trials.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:55.260
So just a few years ago, like Hans Mann, as well as Tufts, we came together to publish

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:58.400
this real world experience of valentamab in patients.

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:02.220
So we had patients with light chain amyloidosis, so we had six total patients where patients

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:06.040
got valentamab and they had exhausted all the other usual therapies.

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:10.080
And we saw that majority of these patients ended up responding to valentamab.

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:13.500
More than half of these patients had achieved a complete response.

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:18.800
And we saw cardiac responses in these patients who were treated with multiple prior lines

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:19.800
of therapy.

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:24.340
Similarly, the UK Amyloid Group also published like their experience of about 30 patients

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:28.360
where they showed that majority of the patients with AL amyloidosis were treated with valentamab.

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:36.280
And we see a similar toxicity profile between amyloidosis and myeloma where keratopathy is

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:40.460
basically the most common toxicity seen in these patients.

00:04:40.460 --> 00:04:43.780
And we see some risk of infections that comes along with it.

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:48.140
And what was important to point out here out of the UK group was that in their 30 patients,

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:52.740
the time to next treatment was close to like two and a half years, which was amazing for

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:57.500
a time in this disease where we had no other therapies available.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:58.320
And then.

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:01.820
Soon after that, we also had a phase two trial that was run in Europe.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:07.940
It's the EMN 27 trial that also included around 30 patients who were treated with valentamab.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:09.820
Valentamab was given every six weeks.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:13.440
And we saw something similar to like what had been previously reported by us in the

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:18.220
real world experience that majority of the patients do respond to valentamab.

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:21.420
And we can see organ responses in these patients.

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:25.280
So just to think of like where things stand with light chain amyloidosis in the upfront

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:27.280
setting, there are cybordi is the clear cut winner.

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:28.280
We have had some trials.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:31.680
We've had some trials in the past, but we can obviously point out like what's the winner

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:35.080
here when it comes to treating newly diagnosed patients.

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:39.300
But I think the future is coming where we will have other options come available, especially

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.040
some of the trials that are coming out.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:45.700
There is a Bella cybordi trial that's coming out for newly diagnosed amyloidosis.

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:50.720
And there are some bispecific trials that are also coming out for newly diagnosed amyloidosis.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:54.480
And I think if some of the real world, as well as like, you know, the early clinical

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:58.240
trial data that's available, it looks like, you know, when patients will get these types

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:03.260
of therapies, majority of them will have a hematologic response, whether that will

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:05.380
translate into an organ response or not.

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:10.820
I think that's something to be seen because a lot of times, even with very effective hematologic

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:16.020
therapy, like hematologic responses in our patients with the amyloidosis organ responses

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:17.780
are seldom seen.

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:23.100
And I think just to end with like, you know, where we are thinking of using the bispecifics,

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:27.800
the CAR-T cell therapy and the ADCs, I think it's certainly a challenge for us.

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:30.440
These are some of the options that are already available.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:33.700
These are some of the options that are already in phase three clinical trials and are going

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:36.160
to be available in the next few years.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:40.500
And then I think when it comes to making this choice, just to reiterate Dr. Martin's point,

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:45.840
that thinking of valentamab's role, like it'll be probably used for patients who have like,

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:51.240
you know, limitations to access like limitations in terms of like caregiver support, patients

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:55.820
who have a very high risk of infections, a profile like that might be a patient who will

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:57.760
be thinking of using valentamab.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:02.320
And at the same time, I think like one of the uses we have found us increasingly like,

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:06.080
you know, consider in our patients is patients who have progressed after CAR-T cell therapy

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:10.480
and after Bispecific, we have a few patients at our center who have responded

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:13.320
to valentamab combinations to our surprise.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:17.120
So we are putting together a case series to report that experience.

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:20.760
And with that, I would like to thank you all for hearing.
